# Lab 7 Question 4
# Added additional comments for improved documentation

rescale_01 <- function(vec, na.rm = TRUE) {
  #Stop function if the vector does not contain numeric values, or if the vector length is greater than 1
  if (!is.numeric(vec[1])){
    stop("Error: vector provided is not numeric")
  } else if (length(vec) <= 1) {
    stop("Error: vector length must be greater than 1")
  }
  
  #Using range to get the range of the function
  vec_range <- range(vec, na.rm = TRUE, finite = TRUE)
  
  #Normalizing values from 0 to 1
  vec <- (vec - vec_range[1]) / 
           (vec_range[2] - vec_range[1])
  
  #Removing NA values if the user specifies
  if (na.rm){
    vec <- vec[!is.na(vec)] #https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/remove-na-values-from-vector-in-r/
  }
  return(vec)
}

# Challenge 7 Question 2

NA_outliers <- function(vec, min_value, max_value) {
  stopifnot("Vector must be numeric and min_value must be less than max_value" = is.numeric(vec[1]) & max_value >= min_value)
  vec <- case_when(
    (vec >= min_value & vec <= max_value) ~ vec,
                   .default = NA)
  return(vec)
}

# Challenge 7 Question 2

NA_outliers <- function(vec, min_value, max_value) {
  stopifnot("Vector must be numeric and min_value must be less than max_value" = is.numeric(vec[1]) & max_value >= min_value)
  vec <- case_when(
    (vec >= min_value & vec <= max_value) ~ vec,
                   .default = NA)
  return(vec)
}

#Simulated from numbers 1 through 4 (discrete uniform distribution)

randomBabies <- function(nBabies){
  baby_data <- tibble(parent = 1:nBabies,
                      returned = sample(1:nBabies,
                                        size = nBabies,
                                        replace = TRUE))
  baby_data |>
    filter(returned == 1) |>
    nrow()
  
}

results <- map_int(.x = 1:10000,
                   .f = ~ randomBabies(4)
                   )

glimpse(results)

# Lab 9 Question 4

simulate_means <- function(n, df){
  return(
    map_dbl(.x = 1:n, 
          .f = ~rchisq(n = 100, df = df) |> mean()
          )
  )
}

In this equation, y represents the county-level median weekly infant center-based childcare price, whereas x represents the median household income for that county. #| label: r-2-3
```{r}
# Lab 7 Question 4
# Added additional comments for improved documentation

rescale_01 <- function(vec, na.rm = TRUE) {
  #Stop function if the vector does not contain numeric values, or if the vector length is greater than 1
  if (!is.numeric(vec[1])){
    stop("Error: vector provided is not numeric")
  } else if (length(vec) <= 1) {
    stop("Error: vector length must be greater than 1")
  }
  
  #Using range to get the range of the function
  vec_range <- range(vec, na.rm = TRUE, finite = TRUE)
  
  #Normalizing values from 0 to 1
  vec <- (vec - vec_range[1]) / 
           (vec_range[2] - vec_range[1])
  
  #Removing NA values if the user specifies
  if (na.rm){
    vec <- vec[!is.na(vec)] #https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/remove-na-values-from-vector-in-r/
  }
  return(vec)
}
```

```{r}
#| label: r-3-function-stops
# Challenge 7 Question 2

NA_outliers <- function(vec, min_value, max_value) {
  stopifnot("Vector must be numeric and min_value must be less than max_value" = is.numeric(vec[1]) & max_value >= min_value)
  vec <- case_when(
    (vec >= min_value & vec <= max_value) ~ vec,
                   .default = NA)
  return(vec)
}
```

```{r}
#Simulated from numbers 1 through 4 (discrete uniform distribution)

randomBabies <- function(nBabies){
  baby_data <- tibble(parent = 1:nBabies,
                      returned = sample(1:nBabies,
                                        size = nBabies,
                                        replace = TRUE))
  baby_data |>
    filter(returned == 1) |>
    nrow()
  
}

results <- map_int(.x = 1:10000,
                   .f = ~ randomBabies(4)
                   )

glimpse(results)

```

```{r}
simulate_means <- function(n, df){
  return(
    map_dbl(.x = 1:n, 
          .f = ~rchisq(n = 100, df = df) |> mean()
          )
  )
}
```
